          "body": "The chapter opens by repeating the feeding miracle of chapter 6 — but on Gentile soil and with Gentile-counted baskets. Mark gives us two numbers to track: *twelve* (8:19, Jewish disciples) and *seven* (8:20, Gentile completeness). The disciples participated in both miracles, served the bread with their own hands, picked up the leftover fragments — and still, in the boat in 8:14-21, they discuss having no bread. Jesus's rhetorical demolition of their dullness (8:17-21) deliberately echoes Isaiah 6:9-10 — the same judgment-language Mark applied to outsiders in 4:11-12 now falls on the Twelve. The disciples are blind. And then immediately Mark stages a blind-man healing (8:22-26) that requires *two* touches — a miracle unique to this Gospel — and follows it with a two-stage *confession* (8:29 the title, 8:31 the mission). The structural message is unmistakable: spiritual sight is given progressively, and even the apostles need a second touch."
